1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,480
Here is a problem that sounds simple but turns out to be one of the harder things in AI right

2
00:00:05,480 --> 00:00:06,580
now.

3
00:00:06,580 --> 00:00:11,920
You point an agent at your whole codebase or your company's entire knowledge base.

4
00:00:11,920 --> 00:00:17,400
That's millions of tokens far more than fits in its context window.

5
00:00:17,400 --> 00:00:22,400
Then you ask one question and the answer lives in maybe three sentences buried somewhere

6
00:00:22,400 --> 00:00:23,820
in all of that.

7
00:00:23,820 --> 00:00:27,400
So how does the agent find those three sentences?

8
00:00:27,400 --> 00:00:33,240
If it dumps everything in, it slows down, it costs more, and it actually gets less accurate

9
00:00:33,240 --> 00:00:35,320
which we covered last time.

10
00:00:35,320 --> 00:00:37,520
The real skill is the opposite.

11
00:00:37,520 --> 00:00:43,000
Pulling in only the right context exactly when it's needed, that's retrieval.

12
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:45,640
And it's changed a lot recently.

13
00:00:45,640 --> 00:00:46,400
Let's walk through it.

14
00:00:46,767 --> 00:00:52,827
let's frame the problem because it's the whole game your context window is small

15
00:00:52,827 --> 00:00:58,407
the information the agent might need is enormous and you can't preload all of it

16
00:00:58,407 --> 00:01:04,427
first because it doesn't fit and second because even if it did buying the answer

17
00:01:04,427 --> 00:01:10,147
in a mountain of irrelevant text makes the model worse not better so instead

18
00:01:10,147 --> 00:01:15,587
you let the model reach out and grab the exact piece it needs the moment it needs

19
00:01:15,587 --> 00:01:21,347
it and nothing else that's all retrieval is the right context on demand you

20
00:01:21,347 --> 00:01:26,147
already know the basic version that's a rag but the gap between a toy rag demo

21
00:01:26,147 --> 00:01:30,687
and the retrieval that holds up in production is large and closing that gap

22
00:01:30,687 --> 00:01:36,807
is the rest of this video it starts somewhere most people overlook

23
00:01:35,467 --> 00:01:39,467
You already know the basic loop, embed your docs,

24
00:01:39,467 --> 00:01:42,667
embed the query, grab the nearest chunks.

25
00:01:42,667 --> 00:01:45,547
We will skip that because what actually decides

26
00:01:45,547 --> 00:01:49,767
whether retrieval works happens earlier at indexing time

27
00:01:49,767 --> 00:01:52,307
and most setups get it wrong.

28
00:01:52,307 --> 00:01:53,807
Start with chunking.

29
00:01:53,807 --> 00:01:55,907
The moment you split a document up,

30
00:01:55,907 --> 00:01:58,887
each chunk loses the context around it.

31
00:01:58,887 --> 00:02:03,807
A line like the fee is $50 gets stored as a naked blob

32
00:02:03,807 --> 00:02:07,767
with no record that it lived under Section 4 refunds.

33
00:02:07,767 --> 00:02:10,187
Retrieve it later and the model has no idea

34
00:02:10,187 --> 00:02:11,767
what it's looking at.

35
00:02:11,767 --> 00:02:14,307
Chunks too big and you drag in noise.

36
00:02:14,307 --> 00:02:16,447
Too small and you lose the meaning.

37
00:02:16,447 --> 00:02:18,387
This one decision sets a ceiling

38
00:02:18,387 --> 00:02:20,827
on how good your system can get.

39
00:02:20,827 --> 00:02:23,027
There's a useful upgrade here.

40
00:02:23,027 --> 00:02:26,007
Anthropic calls it contextual retrieval.

41
00:02:26,007 --> 00:02:29,747
Before you embed a chunk, a cheap model writes a short note

42
00:02:29,747 --> 00:02:33,487
on where it sits in the document and prepends it.

43
00:02:33,487 --> 00:02:37,067
So the fee is $50 becomes in the refund policy,

44
00:02:37,067 --> 00:02:38,787
the fee is $50.

45
00:02:38,787 --> 00:02:42,107
Same chunk, but now it carries its context.

46
00:02:42,107 --> 00:02:44,987
In an anthropic own testing, that single change

47
00:02:44,987 --> 00:02:48,907
to the embedding's cut field retrievals by about a third

48
00:02:48,907 --> 00:02:52,187
before you have even touched the search.

49
00:02:52,187 --> 00:02:55,707
Fix the index and everything downstream gets easier.

50
00:02:56,167 --> 00:03:00,967
With a solid index, the next question is the search itself.

51
00:03:00,967 --> 00:03:03,667
And there is a result here worth knowing.

52
00:03:03,667 --> 00:03:07,167
Semantic search is good at understanding what you mean.

53
00:03:07,167 --> 00:03:12,707
Ask how do I reset my password and it finds a doc titled account recovery steps with no

54
00:03:12,707 --> 00:03:14,527
matching words at all.

55
00:03:14,527 --> 00:03:15,687
That's powerful.

56
00:03:15,687 --> 00:03:21,847
But it has a blind spot, exact terms, error codes, product IDs, a function name.

57
00:03:21,847 --> 00:03:28,207
The meaning matching blurs those out and on some 2026 benchmarks, plain keyword search

58
00:03:28,207 --> 00:03:31,507
actually beat vector search outright.

59
00:03:31,507 --> 00:03:34,087
So the better systems use both.

60
00:03:34,087 --> 00:03:39,667
That's hybrid search, run keyword and semantic together and merge the rankings.

61
00:03:39,667 --> 00:03:43,527
One catches the exact terms, the other catches the meaning.

62
00:03:43,527 --> 00:03:46,487
Then there is one more layer, re-ranking.

63
00:03:46,487 --> 00:03:50,127
Hybrid pulls a wide set, say 50 candidates.

64
00:03:50,127 --> 00:03:54,707
A second smarter model rereads those 50 and resorts them.

65
00:03:54,707 --> 00:04:00,327
So the best three rise to the top, cast a wide net quickly, then let a specialist pick

66
00:04:00,327 --> 00:04:01,847
the winners.

67
00:04:01,847 --> 00:04:08,327
Stack all of it, contextual embeddings, hybrid search and a re-rangle and in anthropic's

68
00:04:08,327 --> 00:04:12,847
own testing, failed retrievals drop by about two thirds.

69
00:04:12,847 --> 00:04:17,967
Same documents, same model, it just finds the right context far more often.

70
00:04:17,967 --> 00:04:19,747
That's the modern retrieval stack.

71
00:04:20,600 --> 00:04:24,960
Now to the part that's genuinely changing right now.

72
00:04:24,960 --> 00:04:30,520
In classic RAG, retrieval happens once before the model even starts thinking.

73
00:04:30,520 --> 00:04:33,240
Agentic retrieval asks a different question.

74
00:04:33,240 --> 00:04:36,060
What if the model drove the search itself?

75
00:04:36,060 --> 00:04:40,400
It's essentially the agent loop pointed at search.

76
00:04:40,400 --> 00:04:41,680
Here is what changes.

77
00:04:41,680 --> 00:04:46,680
The agent takes your question and reformulates it into a better query.

78
00:04:46,680 --> 00:04:51,320
If it's complex, it breaks it into sub-questions and searches each one.

79
00:04:51,320 --> 00:04:55,280
Then the key part, it looks at what came back and judges it.

80
00:04:55,280 --> 00:04:56,280
Do I have enough?

81
00:04:56,280 --> 00:05:00,040
No, the answer references something I haven't looked up yet.

82
00:05:00,040 --> 00:05:05,080
So it searches again and keeps going until it has what it needs.

83
00:05:05,080 --> 00:05:09,600
Instead of one blind grab, you get a small research loop.

84
00:05:09,600 --> 00:05:15,600
Ask something that takes three hops to answer and classic RAG tends to fall apart.

85
00:05:15,600 --> 00:05:19,440
While an agentic retrieval chains the hops and gets there.

86
00:05:19,440 --> 00:05:20,800
This isn't free though.

87
00:05:20,800 --> 00:05:25,060
It costs roughly three to ten times the tokens of classic RAG.

88
00:05:25,060 --> 00:05:30,040
So use it where the question is genuinely hard not to look up a simple fact.

89
00:05:30,533 --> 00:05:33,673
It also doesn't have to happen up front.

90
00:05:33,673 --> 00:05:38,753
The agent can retrieve mid-task the moment it hits something it doesn't know.

91
00:05:38,753 --> 00:05:43,513
Take a coding agent, it's editing a file, hits a function it doesn't recognize, and

92
00:05:43,513 --> 00:05:49,353
right there in the loop it runs a search, grabs just that definition and moves on.

93
00:05:49,353 --> 00:05:55,193
Retrieval becomes a tool the agent calls whenever it has a gap, just in time rather than just

94
00:05:55,193 --> 00:05:56,513
in case.

95
00:05:56,513 --> 00:06:03,433
And it's not only documents, the same machinery works on memory, past conversations, decisions,

96
00:06:03,433 --> 00:06:05,073
notes about the user.

97
00:06:05,073 --> 00:06:10,473
When something's relevant, the agent searches its own memory and pulls back the one item

98
00:06:10,473 --> 00:06:13,273
that matters out of thousands.

99
00:06:13,273 --> 00:06:15,273
Find the needle, leave the haystack.

100
00:06:15,433 --> 00:06:20,553
At this point you might be thinking, we have million token windows now, can't I just put

101
00:06:20,553 --> 00:06:23,193
everything in and skip all this?

102
00:06:23,193 --> 00:06:26,833
Mostly no, those large windows are slow and expensive.

103
00:06:26,833 --> 00:06:32,273
One analysis clogged a long context query at tens of seconds and pennies to dollars

104
00:06:32,273 --> 00:06:37,873
each versus retrieval at about a second for a small fraction of the cost.

105
00:06:37,873 --> 00:06:42,393
And even with a giant window, models still miss facts buried in the middle.

106
00:06:42,393 --> 00:06:47,073
It's a real effect, though how strong it is depends on the model.

107
00:06:47,073 --> 00:06:49,913
So the better teams don't choose one or the other.

108
00:06:49,913 --> 00:06:56,473
They use retrieval to narrow a million documents down to the handful few that matter then let

109
00:06:56,473 --> 00:07:00,393
the large window reason over that focused set.

110
00:07:00,393 --> 00:07:02,513
Retrieval and long context working together.

111
00:07:02,833 --> 00:07:07,153
Step back because this changes how you build agents.

112
00:07:07,153 --> 00:07:09,993
We tend to focus on which model is smartest,

113
00:07:09,993 --> 00:07:12,593
but the more useful framing is this.

114
00:07:12,593 --> 00:07:15,793
An agent is only as good as what it can find

115
00:07:15,793 --> 00:07:18,753
and bring into focus at the right moment.

116
00:07:18,753 --> 00:07:20,493
The smartest model available

117
00:07:20,493 --> 00:07:22,853
looking at the wrong three paragraphs

118
00:07:22,853 --> 00:07:25,873
just gives you a confident wrong answer.

119
00:07:25,873 --> 00:07:29,733
So retrieval is how the agent sees, it's the sensors.

120
00:07:29,733 --> 00:07:33,753
Get it right and an ordinary model starts to feel sharp

121
00:07:33,753 --> 00:07:35,913
because every time it answers,

122
00:07:35,913 --> 00:07:38,353
it's looking at exactly what it needs.

123
00:07:38,353 --> 00:07:41,153
That's the skill worth focusing on right now.

124
00:07:41,267 --> 00:07:44,967
Quick recap of how agents find the right context.

125
00:07:44,967 --> 00:07:46,887
It starts at indexing.

126
00:07:46,887 --> 00:07:50,847
Contextual retrieval, so your chunks carry their meaning.

127
00:07:50,847 --> 00:07:53,847
Then hybrid search plus a re-ranker

128
00:07:53,847 --> 00:07:56,487
pulls and sorts the best results.

129
00:07:56,487 --> 00:07:59,927
Agentic retrieval lets the model run a real search loop

130
00:07:59,927 --> 00:08:03,047
going multi-step until it has the answer.

131
00:08:03,047 --> 00:08:05,807
It retrieves just-in-time mid-task

132
00:08:05,807 --> 00:08:08,267
and works on memory the same way.

133
00:08:08,267 --> 00:08:11,567
And large context windows don't replace any of this.

134
00:08:11,567 --> 00:08:13,447
They work alongside it.

135
00:08:13,447 --> 00:08:16,987
If this made things clearer, hit like and subscribe.

136
00:08:16,987 --> 00:08:18,627
It genuinely helps the channel

137
00:08:18,627 --> 00:08:21,107
and there's a whole series on building agents

138
00:08:21,107 --> 00:08:22,547
that actually work.

139
00:08:22,547 --> 00:08:23,747
See you in the next one.
